<html>
	<head>
		<title>Printer Page</title>
		<meta http-equiv="Content-Language" content="en-us">
		<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=windows-1252">
	</head>
	<body>
		<p><IMG alt="" src="Printer.jpg"></p>
		<p>This is the Printing page of the Brainchild configuration program. With it you can 
			change the way the text is printed, wether or not header and/or footer strings 
			are printed and if syntax coloring is to be used. The various settings are 
			explaned below:</p>
		<table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellPadding="2">
			<tr>
				<td width="35%">Print header</td>
				<td width="65%">When this option is checked Brainchild will print a header line at the 
					start of each page.&nbsp; Under this option you see three edit controls. The 
					contents of the left edit control is printed left-aligned, the contents of the 
					middle edit control is printed centered and the contents of the right edit 
					control is printed right-aligned. See the <a href="#formats">Header and Footer format 
						elements</a> section for information on the possible format elements.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td width="35%">Print footer</td>
				<td width="65%">When this option is checked Brainchild will print a footer line at the 
					end of each page.&nbsp; Under this option you see three edit controls. The 
					contents of the left edit control is printed left-aligned, the contents of the 
					middle edit control is printed centered and the contents of the right edit 
					control is printed right-aligned. See the <a href="#formats">Header and Footer format 
						elements</a> section for information on the possible format elements.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td width="35%">Use syntax coloring when printing</td>
				<td width="65%">When this option is turned on and you have a color printer Brainchild 
					will use syntax coloring during the printing of the file. Note that the 
					background color for the default text, I.E. text which does not have it's own 
					background color defined, will not be printed.</td>
			</tr>
			<TR>
				<TD width="35%">Print line numbers</TD>
				<TD width="65%">When this option is turned on the line numbers will also be printed.</TD>
			</TR>
			<TR>
				<TD width="35%">Use screen font for printing</TD>
				<TD width="65%">When this option is turned on the control will use the font used to 
					display the file on screen for it's printer output aswell.</TD>
			</TR>
			<tr>
				<td width="35%">Use selected font for printing</td>
				<td width="65%">When this option is selected the control will use the font you can 
					select using the <b>Select...</b> button.</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td width="35%">
					Select...</td>
				<td width="65%">Click on this button to change the type-face and font size used to 
					print the file. This option is only available when you have selected the 
					"Selected printer font" option. You can only select fixed width fonts.</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
		<p><a name="formats"></a><font size="5"><b><a name="formats">Header and Footer format elements</a></b></font></p>
		<p>The header and footer strings can contain any of the following format elements:</p>
		<p>
			<table border="1" cellpadding="2" width="100%" cellspacing="1">
				<tr>
					<td width="10%" bgcolor="#e4e4e4"><b>Element</b></td>
					<td width="90%" bgcolor="#e4e4e4"><b>Meaning</b></td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%%</td>
					<td width="90%">Insert a % character in the output.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%f</td>
					<td width="90%">The filename of the text without the path.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%F</td>
					<td width="90%">The full path of the text.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%p</td>
					<td width="90%">The page number currently being printed.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%P</td>
					<td width="90%">The total number of pages to print.</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%d</td>
					<td width="90%">The date of printing. Formatted using the format string set of the <a href="date_page.htm">
							Date &amp; Time</a> page.
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td width="10%">%d</td>
					<td width="90%">The time of printing. Formatted using the format string set of the <a href="date_page.htm">
							Date &amp; Time</a> page.
					</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
		<p>All other characters are printed exactly as they appear in the format string.</p>
	</body>
</html>
